Chet,<br><br>
Good questions!<br><br>
I bounced around a lot, from basecamp to basecamp, bush to bush, FSB to FSB, so I saw things and did things that I quess fell into most everyone's experience at one time or other. No Audie Murphy or porkchop hill stuff. I was one of the guys in the bunker with all the antennas on top with the battle map and a dozen or so radios in control of a dozen artillery batteries doing fire missions for the guys in hot lz's, contacts, pz's, ndp's and a whole lot more acronyms I have probably forgotten. Part of the job was to keep from knocking the fly boys out of the air and keeping out of those no fire zones, the vc havens around all the villes. That made for some tricky shots, especially if they wanted the rounds walked in real close. B52's get outa my way!<br><br>
1800 to 0600, seven days a week. The antennas didn't attract lightning, they attracted mortars and rockets. They used to pop them off in the day. Really ruined my sleep!<br><br>
Bugs, snakes, mold, rot, rats, dead rats, millions of tiny frogs that would crunch under your feet, Chu Hoi, our frog eating mascot mutt, the little green snakes in the shower that sent Mama-sans shrieking, and, yes, the five foot pit viper that decided to live under my bunk, and all the other stuff.<br><br>
Screams of guys over the radio in the night, frustration, victory, the relentless pounding, caring, fear, and all that other stuff too.<br><br>
I consider myself just as much a Vietnam Vet as the next guy. I did my thing. I did it well. I burned out my brain doing it. I kept guys from getting blown away. I blew away some not so friendly fellows.<br><br>
The REMF stuff was just one of the caste systems people always try to shove down your throat. Football/cheerleader stuff. We all had our own way of looking at things, mostly to keep your sanity, and identification with one group or other kept things sort of together. It was always the other guy who was the you know what.<br><br>
I don't care what others may think. I was there, it was real, and I have stuff on my wall that says it was. I am more concerned with what it did to guys in the aftermath than what they may have done or not done.<br><br>
Emotional and physical pain is the real bottom line. We all hurt the same way.   
